        <name>4.5.3.2 C as A and B</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;By squaring and adding the equations \(A=C\cos\alpha\) and \(B=C\sin \alpha\), obtain \(C\) in terms of \(A\) and \(B\). You can assume \(C&amp;gt;0\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(C = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;By eliminating \( C \) from the equations \(A=C\cos\alpha\) and \(B=C\sin \alpha\), obtain \(\tan\alpha \) in terms of \(A\) and \(B.\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\tan\alpha = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;\(A= C\cos\alpha\)&amp;nbsp; and \(B=C\sin\alpha\) gives&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[ \quad A^2+B^2=C^2\cos^2\alpha+C^2\sin^2\alpha=C^2(\cos^2\alpha+\sin^2\alpha)=C^2\] therefore \( C=\sqrt{A^2+B^2}\) (We take the positive square root.)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;By division, \( \dfrac{B}{A}=\dfrac{C\sin\alpha}{C\cos\alpha}=\tan\alpha\).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Furthermore, \(\alpha\) can be obtained by solving \(\tan\alpha=\dfrac{B}{A}\). However, care must be taken to obtain the correct quadrant for \(\alpha.\)&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
